You can use the following function to check if any number in an array of 5 numbers is a prime number and print the prime number(s) to the console:
```javascript
function checkPrimeNumbers(arr) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if (isPrime(arr[i])) {
      console.log(arr[i]);
    }
  }
}

function isPrime(num) {
  if (num < 2) return false;
  if (num === 2) return true;
  if (num % 2 === 0 || num % 3 === 0) return false;
  if (num < 100 && num !== 2 && num !== 3) return true;
  for (let i = 5; i * i <= num; i += 6) {
    if (num % i === 0 || num % (i + 2) === 0) return false;
  }
  return true;
}
```
The `checkPrimeNumbers()` function takes an array of 5 numbers and loops through each number using the `isPrime()` function to check if it is a prime number. If a number is a prime number, it is printed to the console.

The `isPrime()` function uses a series of checks to determine if a number is prime. The function is optimized for small numbers up to 100, and for numbers greater than 100, it uses a more exhaustive but efficient method based on trial division by small primes.

